Let=E2=80=99s get started=E2=80=A6

Julie Davich
Julie Davich

Maarten ten
Holder

An Art World Brokerage Play
---------------------------

When I caught up with Charlie
Horne, president of the appraisal and advisory firm Gurr Johns, he was on h=
is way to the Heckerling Institute on Estate Planning in Orlando. Heckerlin=
g, as the gathering is known in the industry, is about as exciting as you=
=E2=80=99d imagine for a conference of estate lawyers and bankers=E2=80=94b=
ut the event does offer an essential glad-handing opportunity for auction h=
ouses and appraisal firms. Charlie will no doubt be touting the news that M=
aarten ten
Holder is joining Gurr Johns as C.E.O. to oversee the firm=E2=80=99s growth=
 strategy, first in the U.S. and then globally.=C2=A0=C2=A0

=C2=A0

Ten Holder spent nearly 25 years at Sotheby=E2=80=99s, shuttling back and f=
orth in operational roles between Europe and New York before taking over th=
e global luxury business and then the classic car division after the acquis=
ition of RM. Most recently, he was at Bonhams
for three years heading up its very British =E2=80=9CMotoring department.=
=E2=80=9D He arrived at Gurr Johns last week after a six-month gardening le=
ave.=C2=A0

=C2=A0

Gurr Johns=E2=80=99 core business for the past 110 years has been appraisal=
s=E2=80=94a somewhat limited service offering, given the time and expertise=
 involved, as well as the general frugality of clients. Indeed, most collec=
tors view the process as a necessary evil to
placate their insurance companies and tax advisors, rather than as an inves=
tment of sorts. Gurr Johns also offers advisory services, which comprise on=
ly a small part of the business and are usually just an upsell on the appra=
isal relationships. Unsurprisingly, ten Holder is expected to operationaliz=
e and expand this channel.

=C2=A0

The firm, as I discussed with ten Holder, is also looking to launch a broke=
rage
offering. Gurr Johns inaugurated its new Paris office this past fall with a=
 private selling exhibition of 20 cubist portraits=E2=80=94including a Pica=
sso paper collage that sold at Christie=E2=80=99s in 2014 for $4.3 million=
=E2=80=94and its London team has mounted shows of primary-market works for =
the past few years. That=E2=80=99s not a big deal for a firm that appraised=
 $15 billion in art last year and has a massive database to match sellers w=
ith buyers. As Marion
noted ( https://puck.news/why-the-art-market-has-entered-a-private-sales-er=
a/?utm_campaign=3DWall+Power+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%281%2F14%2F25%29&utm_content=3D=
Wall+Power+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%281%2F14%2F25%29&utm_medium=3Demail_action&utm_so=
urce=3Dcustomer.io&utm_term=3Df6c60617da42abd12a ) on Sunday, auction sales=
 are still mired in a downturn, but private sales have been thriving, espec=
ially after the November elections.=C2=A0

=C2=A0

Standing up a brokerage business is rife with challenges, of course. Gurr J=
ohns built its core business on the trust of clients
who largely don=E2=80=99t want the auction houses to know what=E2=80=99s in=
 their portfolio and make deals on that information. Indeed, the words =E2=
=80=9Cindependent=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=9Cnonconflicted=E2=80=9D take pride o=
f place in company marketing materials. Will this new brokerage business un=
dercut that positioning?

=C2=A0

Ten Holder seems aware of the delicacy of the task. Horne suggested that th=
e difference between Gurr Johns=E2=80=99 brokerage and the private sales ar=
mies at
the big galleries and auction houses would come down to the appraiser=E2=80=
=99s pricing expertise. =E2=80=9CUnderstanding value,=E2=80=9D he told me, =
=E2=80=9Cis how to sell something well.=E2=80=9D

A Tale of Two Cranachs
----------------------

Lucas Cranach the Elder, Hercules and Omphale, estimated at $1,000,000

From time to time, similar works by the same artist come up for auction in =
the same
season. A few weeks ago, an art advisor was quick to point out that Sotheby=
=E2=80=99s and Christie=E2=80=99s had both just announced similar work by L=
ucas Cranach the Elder depicting Hercules in submission to the princess Omp=
hale in their early February Old Master sales. Christie=E2=80=99s, which is=
 selling ( https://www.christies.com/en/lot/lot-6520225?utm_campaign=3DWall=
+Power+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%281%2F14%2F25%29&utm_content=3DWall+Power+-+SUBSCRIBE=
RS+%281%2F14%2F25%29&utm_medium=3Demail_action&utm_source=3Dcustomer.io&utm=
_term=3Df6c60617da42abd12a ) the slightly more expensive version, Hercules =
and Omphale, with an
estimate of $1 million, notes in their marketing materials that Cranach pai=
nted at least 35 of these images, which portray Hercules emasculated by wea=
ring a bonnet and grasping a distaff, the weaving tool that was associated =
with women=E2=80=99s work. The paintings come from a genre called weibermac=
ht, which cautioned against the supposed dangers of women gaining power. Th=
ere are other classical subjects used to illustrate the idea of weakened me=
n, but the Hercules and Omphale theme is
=E2=80=9Cspecific to Cranach,=E2=80=9D the Sotheby=E2=80=99s old master spe=
cialist Daria Foner told me. =E2=80=9CThe throughline is the admonition to =
beware of the wiles and power of women.=E2=80=9D

Lucas Cranach the Elder and Workshop, Hercules at the Court of Omphale,
estimated at $700,000

By comparison, Sotheby=E2=80=99s version of Hercules in the Court of
Omphale, from 1533, is estimated ( https://www.sothebys.com/en/buy/auction/=
2025/master-paintings-sculpture-part-i/hercules-at-the-court-of-omphale?utm=
_campaign=3DWall+Power+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%281%2F14%2F25%29&utm_content=3DWall+P=
ower+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%281%2F14%2F25%29&utm_medium=3Demail_action&utm_source=
=3Dcustomer.io&utm_term=3Df6c60617da42abd12a ) at $700,000. The work was am=
ong the first to be painted in the popular series=E2=80=94a brief run that =
would last five or six years. Foner suggested the imagery may have become t=
oo popular, and Cranach simply moved on.=C2=A0

Cranach has
seen his status rise in the market of late. When a new record for the artis=
t was set at $14.3 million, in 2015, the price seemed like an outlier for a=
 long time. But time moves at a different pace in the old master world. (Af=
ter all, both of the Cranachs depicting Hercules have been in their consign=
ors=E2=80=99 collections for more than 20 years.) In 2018, Cranach=E2=80=99=
s portrait John Frederick I, Elector of Saxony, made $7.7 million. Then in =
2022, The Nymph of the Spring, which features a
full-length nude with a diaphanous veil, sold for $11.3 million. Two of the=
 figures in Christie=E2=80=99s Hercules painting have similar veils. Indeed=
, Foner pointed out that classical figures in =E2=80=9Cstylized present-day=
 clothing=E2=80=9D was one of Cranach=E2=80=99s signature innovations. The =
artist, said Foner, had a =E2=80=9Csuperb way of rendering fabric, and you =
see that in the costumes that he paints, which gives him an enduring appeal=
=2E=E2=80=9D

