The strength and quality of an artist=E2=80=99s studio or foundation can be
the difference between their legacy dissipating into the ether or gathering=
 strength with time. And soon enough, Beard=E2=80=99s own fate might be dec=
ided.

Marion Maneker ( https://puck.news/author/marion-maneker/?utm_campaign=3DWa=
ll+Power+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%281%2F14%2F25%29&utm_content=3DWall+Power+-+SUBSCRI=
BERS+%281%2F14%2F25%29&utm_medium=3Demail_action&utm_source=3Dcustomer.io&u=
tm_term=3Df6c60617da42abd12a )
Marion Maneker ( https://puck.news/author/marion-maneker/?utm_campaign=3DWa=
ll+Power+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%281%2F14%2F25%29&utm_content=3DWall+Power+-+SUBSCRI=
BERS+%281%2F14%2F25%29&utm_medium=3Demail_action&utm_source=3Dcustomer.io&u=
tm_term=3Df6c60617da42abd12a )

Peter Beard=E2=80=99s extraordinary life=E2=80=94do we have the
space to list all of the artists (Francis Bacon, Andy Warhol) and models (C=
heryl Tiegs, Iman) and writers (Karen Blixen, Truman Capote) and society fi=
gures (Lee Radziwill) with whom he collided?=E2=80=94was messy. He made his=
 name, beyond the rewards of his preternatural good looks, as a photographe=
r and adventurer=E2=80=94traveling between Kenya and Montauk, with long pau=
ses in
Manhattan nightclubs, taking photographs and keeping voluminous diaries. Ov=
er time, the border between his life and art=E2=80=94often hand-worked with=
 text and drawings and the story of his life=E2=80=94which was never easily=
 defined, would disappear completely.

=C2=A0

In early 2020, Beard, suffering from dementia and the after-effects of a st=
roke, wandered away from his Montauk home and died in the woods at the age =
of 82. Now,
after years of a slowing market, Beard's studio is trying to reassert itsel=
f. Last month, lawyers for the studio, run ( https://nymag.com/news/feature=
s/peter-beard-2013-3/index1.html?utm_campaign=3DWall+Power+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%2=
81%2F14%2F25%29&utm_content=3DWall+Power+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%281%2F14%2F25%29&ut=
m_medium=3Demail_action&utm_source=3Dcustomer.io&utm_term=3Df6c60617da42abd=
12a ) by his widow, Nejma, filed a lawsuit against Heritage Auctions. At di=
spute is the sale ( https://fineart.ha.com/c/auction-home.zx?saleNo=3D17203=
&ic=3Dbreadcrumb-fineart-121913-interior&utm_campaign=3DWall+Power+-+SUBSCR=
IBERS+%281%2F14%2F25%29&utm_content=3DWall+Power+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%281%2F14%2F=
25%29&utm_medium=3Demail_action&utm_source=3Dcustomer.io&utm_term=3Df6c6061=
7da42abd12a )
of 51 lots held on October 25 entitled In Focus: Peter Beard Showcase, of w=
hich 38 lots were sold for $97,669. (A portion of the proceeds was meant to=
 go to a charity called Aprile=E2=80=99s Memorial French Bulldogs Special N=
eeds Support Services.)=C2=A0

The studio argues that the consignor never had a right to sell the items, a=
nd is upset that Heritage did not consult with them about the nature of the=
 materials before the sale. Some of the
material, they contend, belong with the estate of Karen Blixen, the Danish =
adventurer and resident of Kenya. Many of the lots were manuscripts or pers=
onal photographs, diary pages, or even books, including Beard=E2=80=99s per=
sonal copy of Blixen=E2=80=99s Out of Africa.=C2=A0

=C2=A0

Once the studio was aware of the sale, the lawsuit asserts, they tried to c=
ontact Heritage to tell the auction house the works were in fact
Beard=E2=80=99s personal effects, journals, and ephemera, and thus should n=
ot be marketed and sold as examples of his art. Indeed, the studio objected=
 to the idea of a single-artist sale without any of the artist=E2=80=99s ac=
tual work. They never heard back from Heritage. =E2=80=9CAs a last resort, =
the studio brings this lawsuit,=E2=80=9D the filing states, =E2=80=9Cto sig=
nal clearly to Heritage=E2=80=94and the market generally=E2=80=94that it wi=
ll not tolerate this type of blatant disregard for the integrity of Beard=
=E2=80=99s body of work, and his
artistic legacy.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0

In other words, the studio seems most concerned with asserting ( https://ny=
mag.com/news/features/peter-beard-2013-3/index1.html?utm_campaign=3DWall+Po=
wer+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%281%2F14%2F25%29&utm_content=3DWall+Power+-+SUBSCRIBERS+=
%281%2F14%2F25%29&utm_medium=3Demail_action&utm_source=3Dcustomer.io&utm_te=
rm=3Df6c60617da42abd12a ) its role as the arbiter of what is, and what is n=
ot, a Beard work of art. Established in 2001 to address the haphazard way t=
hat Beard dealt with his work since the mid-1980s, the studio is tasked wit=
h creating an archive of his artwork, complete with
inventory numbers, to help authenticate pieces, as well as order and preser=
ve his many journals. Before he died, Beard was an active participant in th=
e studio=E2=80=99s work. He edited books about his own work; helped authent=
icate work and monitor the market for his unique objects; and worked with t=
he archivist to create a database. And, as the only source for artwork by B=
eard, the studio has an interest in policing his secondary market.

The Legacy Question
-------------------

With fewer catalogues raisonn=C3=A9 being published these days,
and the need for more responsive databases, artists=E2=80=99 studios and es=
tates have turned to providing archive numbers as evidence of authenticatio=
n=E2=80=94a fairly responsive resource that helps define an object and situ=
ate it within the body of the artist=E2=80=99s work. Some estates or studio=
s=E2=80=94such as those of Philip Guston, Roy Lichtenstein, and Gerhard Ric=
hter=E2=80=94have comprehensive databases that are available to the public.=
 Others, like the Calder Foundation,
have closed systems. Good record-keeping and a responsive studio or estate =
are often necessary, though not necessarily sufficient, conditions to grow =
an artist=E2=80=99s market.=C2=A0=C2=A0

=C2=A0

And Beard=E2=80=99s market needs some growth. Although a large photo collag=
e, Lion at Night, from 1984, sold for $327,000 in May of 2023, it=E2=80=99s=
 been quite some time since top prices advanced for his work. From 2011 to
2017, seven different works sold at auction for prices above $300,000, incl=
uding three that achieved prices above $600,000. Since then, and especially=
 after his harrowing death, the auction market for his work has cooled.=C2=
=A0

One of the shibboleths of the art market is that it is lawless and unregula=
ted. But that=E2=80=99s not true. Auction houses and art dealers are subjec=
t to commercial laws, and more importantly, the market has developed its ow=
n systems of
self-regulation. The strength and quality of an artist=E2=80=99s studio or =
foundation can be the difference between their legacy dissipating into the =
ether or gathering strength with time. A spokesperson for Heritage Auctions=
 said, =E2=80=9CHeritage will be filing a response to this frivolous lawsui=
t within the next two weeks.=E2=80=9D

